<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-196-244  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 196 244.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  March 3 1990 v139 p16(N) p48(L) 27 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bills to pay? The number is ... (bill-paying by telephone)(includes related article about a new phone with a miniatureviewing screen and keyboard, offered by Citibank)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Quint, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Approximately 250 banks now offer pay-by-phone services, accordingto Bruce A. Burchfield, chairman of National Payment ClearingHouse, a business that offers bill-paying services for banks.andO;Telephone bill-paying was introduced in 1973, but many banks thathave offered the service have been disappointed by costs involvedand lack of customer response.andP;  Bill paying services will becomemore attractive to consumers as they become more concerned aboutways to save time instead of money, and the cost of a first-classstamp rises from 25 cents to 30 cents.andP;  Citibank recentlyintroduced an 'enhanced telephone,' which is a specially designedproduct that comes with a miniature viewing screen and a keyboard,facilitating bill-paying and other banking activities.andP;  The phonescost $49.95 to install, with a $9.95 monthly rental fee.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   National Payment Clearing House Inc. (officials and employees)Chase Manhattan Bank (information services).andO;Topic:     Home BankingTelephone CompaniesInformation servicesBankingEFTS.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Burchfield, Bruce A. (attitudes); Kelly, Donald Q. (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>